<!--METADATA-->

[ ![](ConvertedIMGs/dwzh/2023-07-02T06-54-00Z/66051120_303.png)](https://www.dw.com/zh/overlay/image/article/66059244/66051120)The Koreans are "young" at once, one to two years old

(Voice of Germany Chinese) When the Koreans woke up on Wednesday (June 28) in the morning, they found that they were one year younger than Tuesday, and some were even two years younger.

This large -scale "aging" is attributed to the effectiveness of a new law. The law abolish the traditional age calculation method (virtual age) and requires Koreans to use the internationalization method of internationalization.

Lee Wan-Kyu, director of the South Korean Legal Department, said at a press conference on Monday: "We expect legal disputes, complaints and social confusion caused by age computing will greatly reduce."

### Korean people used to use virtual years before

According to the traditional method of calculating the age in South Korea, a person is already one year old when he is born. Everyone's age will increase by one year on January 1, not only the age of birthday.

Although the international age calculation method has been used in South Korea for legal documents and medical documents since the early 1960s, the traditional calculation method is still used in daily life.

But the law passed in December last year ended this traditional system. According to a government polls in September last year, 86% of Koreans plan to use international systems.

"I will be 30 years old next year." Choi Hyun-Ji, a 27-year-old office staff member, told Reuters when talking about the traditional age algorithm. "But now I have more time, it's great."

### "Squid Game" reveal Korean social problems

### Why is the virtual age continued in South Korea to this day?

This traditional algorithm has also been used in other countries in East Asia before, [for example China](https://www.dw.com/zh/zh/汉语拼音之父周有光的岁数/a-17370220), Japan and North Korea, but they were abandoned decades ago.

It continues in South Korea, partly because of the importance of "age" to Korean, because people usually use respect, such as "Unni" (sister) and "OPPA" (brother), not personal names.

"Age is indeed important." Humanologist Mo Hyun-Joo told AFP, "If you don't know people's age, it is difficult to communicate with them."

In the traditional algorithm, everyone in a grade in the school is considered the same age, so we can talk to without a language level.

There are also the third age computing system in South Korea. It is used to calculate a person's school year, when to participate in the compulsory military service, and when to buy alcoholic beverages.

The system is similar to the traditional algorithm, but starts from the age of zero. The system is not affected by new laws and will continue to exist.

(Reuters, Agence France -Presse)

